CQLX Gracemere yarding decreased by 500 to 3429 head. Cattle came to hand from Mackay, Collinsville, Clermont and local areas south to Gin Gin. Quality and condition were generally good with a bigger percentage of the yarding being cows and heifers. Competition from a full field of buyers helped lift cow and heifers lines in processor classes above last weekâ€™s improved rates. This trend carried through much of the sale.

Light weight yearling steers sold to 435c/kg with the best-bred pens averaging 360c to 384 c/kg to restockers. The best of the medium and heavy yearling steers sold to 431c/kg, averaging 390c to 404c/kg to backgrounders and restockers. Best-bred yearling heifers in light pens averaged 261c to 297c/kg- selling to 311c/kg. Medium weight lines made to 343c/kg, averaging 295c to 336c/kg.

Feeder steers made to 409c/kg for grown pens, with averages from 332c to 380c/kg. Processor bullocks reached 331c/kg, averaging 309c to 318c/kg. The best trade heifers returned a top price of 363c/kg to average 334c to 351c/kg for good sized samples. A few grown heifers to feed averaged 278c to 334c/kg.

Restockers cows ranged from 209c/kg average to 251c/kg. Heavy, four score cows topped at 292c/kg, averaging 283 for the best conditioned pens. Heavy bulls to processors averaged 262c/kg whilst those to livex averaged 255c/kg with a top of 285c/kg. Cows and calves also maintained the upward trend of past weeks with the better-bred pens selling from $1,400 to $1,915 per unit. Reporter: Richard Thomson.
